segments.text: What facilities were there across the tracks then for this physical training?
Nothing except the road, and down there there was an animal husbandry thing, which later on I'd go visit and see them doing artificial insemination.
Toward the north?
Toward the north, yes.
There was one building over there, there was a farmhouse.
We'd run down to the farmhouse in the corner there, about where that...
shelter is for Olsen Field, somewhere in that area.
And basically around Olsen Field, back down to Mileshamton.
And they told us they were going to grade us on the time we did it in.
And so you really, where you were fat, if you were not fat, it doesn't make any difference.
They're going to grade you on that.
They didn't do it, but they set the thermos with it.
So you'd be busy till 4 o'clock or so.
Yeah.
Well, and then the afternoon, most of the time, we'd play intramural sports.
Mm-hmm.
It kept us busy.
I mean, there was very little leisure time.
I enjoyed it.
Alright, then back to the room, clean up, fall out, march to evening chow.
Yeah, evening chow.
We'd come back and we had to study with the door open and sit at our desk and have our head down at a book.
So we developed a knack of sleeping in that position.
Describe your room.
Oh, room.
You could not have no carpet, nothing on the walls, one picture of somebody, mother and father, girlfriend, one picture.
Very Spartan.
And at that time, I began to think of A&M and Sparta to Texas University, Athens.
I mean, I was that mold.
I was a typical Aggie.
I thought about it in many ways, and so I thought we were smarter than they were.
We lived a smarter life.
How long did it take you and your fish buddies to start trying some kind of pranks or tricks on the upperclassmen?
It would probably have been close to a semester.
Float out, take a box of scabs, which were corn flakes, soak them in a bucket of water all day,
and then have a great joy of throwing them into somebody's bed with them in the middle of the night and running from the campus cops, the KKs, and jumping in bed, and they're chasing you.
It's laying there in one of the flashlights, and you're pretending you're asleep and getting away with it.
Great joy, great thrill.
Yeah, if anybody got caught, what kind of punishment did they get from the upper class?
The upper class, yeah, well, they'd probably get their tails beat.
With what kind of a paddle?
Uh...
probably a shaved-down baseball bat or softball bat.
Do you remember ever getting a paddle?
I don't remember.
As I said, I lived a very protective life somehow, being, A, not giving anybody a hard time, not wising off to anybody, and, B, having the protection of Mr. Bildevich.
There were some things I could stick in there.

Like Mr. Spears came in one time about 2 o'clock in the morning and woke me up and said his girlfriend was coming in the next morning at 7 o'clock, and I had to get him up at 6 o'clock and sort of go down and beat the train for the girl.
And I didn't wake up sufficient.
I did so long.
I mean, he just woke me up and told me, and my head hit the thing, and I was gone.
The next day he saw me.
He said, who's 40?
I thought I told you to get me up.
I don't remember if you did, but I just, I did not do it deliberately and everything else, but I mean, I was just sound asleep when he woke me up, you know, back to sleep.
When he turned around and turned his heel, I was back sound asleep and totally escaped.
Did he give you any punishment?
No, he did not.
Where did you and your buddies...
go if you had some spare time during the day, just to go to relax, to... Why did you go?
What did you do over there?
Read the newspapers.
I did.
They had newspapers from all over the state.
If anybody wasn't eager to sit there and read them.
Now, I don't want to transpose myself into my coming back to the Marines.
That's difficult.
Mostly, if we didn't play in New York, we'd go out and do pickup athletic games, you know, touch football.
Where, physically, where would y'all play those games?
There were all kinds of empty spaces around the dorms, yeah.
They were locked, they were out in the middle of what now they call the quad, middle of the new area.
There were a drill field all over.
I mean, just, there was never any, all right.
In dorm, what do we call dorm 13, 14,
16 in that area.
There was empty space in between them there.
There were many faculty and staff houses on campus then, weren't there?
Oh, yes.
That's another thing that caught me.
Joe Falk had a house just about where Kane Hall is in that area.
And my parents and other CCC people would come to football games.
And you have open houses pretty much.
And all these old friends would come in there and see each other
Dr. Munson was one of them that they knew, too.
He had been at CCCU.
He was an educational advisor or something.
I don't know what he had done there, but my dad knew him pretty well.
And I don't know how, I don't know, but they would all come in there.
And as a kid, I thought, this is the life.
This is the most beautiful life that I can imagine.
Come in here and see all your friends and then go down to the football game, walk down right to Kyle Field, park out in Simpson Drill Field, go over to the Hawks, then go on into the game.
And everybody there remembering old times and enjoying themselves, catching up on times.
When I came back, I wanted to get as close to the campers as I could.
If I could move right there, I'd move there.
Then on the weekends, what would you all do?
On the weekends during the summer, there was no football games.
Saturday classes, same thing.
I did not go to church.
I never darkened the door of a church.
We'd go to the dances, I guess.
But Saturday night in the summer, there weren't any dances, were there?
There weren't any dances, no.
I mean...
Just entertain ourselves.
Did you go to Guyon?
Were there movies?
We'd go to the campus theater.
We'd go into, catch a ride into Bryan, go to movies at Bryan if we could, get off.
Some of these, you know, I have to go back and thought about these particular questions.
But I do remember walking the streets of Guyon in khaki uniforms.
How did the people of the community react to people, to young men wearing khaki uniforms?
Fine, no problem.
They were used to Aggies here.

I was thinking the other day, coming in here, just think that act of legislature that established the Agricultural Mechanical College of Texas here, and what has developed that one little act, and you look at this big, almost metropolis now, and had they not done that, Bryan would have been probably smaller than that or so.
Do you remember, have any idea what the cost was that first year?
Well, I'll tell you.
Yeah, my brother had a bank account who had lost $900.
And he said he had left instruction that was to be used for my education.
So my mother and father transferred it over to my account.
And I paid my entire first year out of that $900.
It seems to me that...
room was $7 a semester, and board was relatively the same.
And how much spending money did you have?
Well, I was working and I had a checking account on that, so I had sufficient, but I didn't spend much.
I still had money left over at the end of the semester, you know, at the end of the year.
All right, back to, I think I heard a touching item, so that
Much of your education was paid for by your brother's account, and he'd already died in action.
Yeah.
He was missing in action legally at that time.
The war certainly was the topic.
Where did you and your buddies listen to the radio and get war news?
In our room.
What were some of the events that you remember almost where you were when you heard the news, D-Day being one?
Oh, D-Day being one.
Before that, I remember invasion of North Africa.
Let me go through my historical data here.
D-Day, June, and you're about to break out going across France.
Then, next big thing, Battle of the Bulge.
It wasn't a big thing of mine, but we were aware of it.
And I was home on Christmas vacation when that occurred, just before I went to the Marines.
I was just getting ready to go to the Marines.
I didn't know it when I came back from Christmas vacation.
And remember, the semesters transpired over.
We had your Christmas, New Year's break, about three weeks of school after that.
And then it's hard to get back when my parents got worried I was going to report to the Senate.
Right, so you take a full load that summer.
Right.
How cool were those dormitories?
Oh, that's another thing we got in that engineering.
Because we moved from
Walton Hall to Hart Hall.
I was up on the top stoop floor of Hart Hall, corner there.
There was three of us in a room there, big room.
And taking engineering drawing, graded on neateness in August in Texas.
And I'd be doing engineering drawing, sweat just pouring off of us.
I'd take handkerchiefs.
spread the handkerchiefs all over the drawing board and just leave a little space where I was actually making a mark.
Try to keep it, but I almost invariably have failed.
And I decided, hey, for me, I don't like this kind of stuff.
I'd much rather write something.
The junior buddies have slide rules?
Oh, yes.
We all had slide rules.
We wore them like...
Scabbers by our side.
Oh, another thing was here was ASTP, Army Specialized Training Program, and they marched from class to class, about 14 of them in a group, and they all had their slide rules and all those things.
Now, were they, the ASTP, were they treated like Aggies?
No, no.
The ASTP were a separate breed and weren't considered by us to be Aggies.
Where were they housed?
Some were in the dorms.
I don't even, I guess, in the new area.
Okay.
No, I'm not for sure.
They were just around somewhere.
Did you go home much that summer?
No.
No, I didn't.
So you were here all summer.
Here all, pretty much.
Any dates?
No.
Were there any social events?
I don't remember any.
I don't remember any of that summer.
Football season, yes.
But that summer there were no dances, no entertainers.
That summer was pretty something to be, pretty much, I mean, in fact, I did not enjoy that summer.
When they told me to go back, the Marines said, oh, okay.
And I came back, but I enjoyed the fall and couldn't wait to get back from it.
All right, so you come back for the fall semester knowing that you're probably going on active duty at the end of that semester.
Yeah, the end or before it's over even.
My mind was not on my grades and studies, you can understand.
Describe what it was like then to go to your first football games at A&M.
Well, let me go back.
May I go back?
Oh, of course.
It's something that we've gone beyond time.
Oh, okay.
I want to go back to this Hellwood kid and what happened to him.
It was a very bad, terrible situation.

Oh, and to answer some of your questions why I can't remember too much about some of these things, this kid made a mistake and told another freshman that he, it was his parents who wrote or sent his letter.
Mm-hmm.
to the administration.
This other freshman kid was psychotic, neurotic, or something.
And he did things that were absolutely filthy, unexcusable, and everything else.
And so Fishel would drop out of A&M.
Well, he took human excrement, spread it over his underclothes, and things like that.
Unpardonable.
I remember defending.
Other people did that?
He did it.
This one freshman did it.
Oh.
To Hellwood.
Oh, to Hellwood.
Okay.
One freshman to another.
Yeah.
And... And Fish Hellwood dropped out of school and said why he was doing it, though he did not know who had done that.
And so the administration, in their wisdom, and they were not very wise, practiced mass punishment.
And they said for the rest of that semester that any battery fuel artillery would be canvassed.
We couldn't go anywhere, do anything.
And kept it up and kept yelling out.
They wanted to find out who had done that to Fish Hellwood.
And it didn't come forth.
Finally, they said that if we, if Fish Hellwood, the one who had persecuted Fish Hellwood, didn't come forth,
they were going to kick Mr. Bilbeck out of the Corps of Cadets.
Well, Fish, the guy who had done it, was really psycho.
He would take a lady's hat needle and drive it through the keg of his leg.
I've seen him do it.
He came forth at that, because we loved Mr. Bilbeck.
And though he once came confessed, and all of a sudden we were told that we were to report
buildings, which are some housing over there, some wooden housing kind of things, over near where the engineering section is in that area, where the engineering buildings are.
We just told them to fall out at night, about 8 o'clock at night.
We thought they were going to march us to the railroad station and ship us all home.
I never heard such good marching.
We were all hitting together.
We thought we were really going to get it.
And we got over there, and Captain Jack Kimbrough, the brother of John Kimbrough, was a attack officer, and he talked.
And he came over and says, and he totally misread the whole psychology.
He said, now don't hold it against this boy for all he's done against, calling you to get camp was awesome.
The administration had made a hero of this psychotic kid.
It had worked an absolutely reverse.

he had enforced the Aggie traditions, Aggie way of life in a one way, but we didn't know, please understand, we're not condoning what he did, but what they had done was they didn't, they didn't deal with it correctly.
Absolutely, you know, the Army taught me that don't use mass punishment, it just makes an enemy out of the ones that you, make a hero out of those that you think you're making an enemy out of.
And so,
So they didn't even kick him out of school.
He flunked out of school.
He was that stupid, in a way.
It seemed like in that time that the admissions policy at A&M occurred during the first year of school, maybe the first semester, when they flunked out.
About 50% of them dropped out of school after one year, not the first semester.
The freshman year was pretty tough, and it was kind of a separate.
They didn't have what you called...
limited selective enrollment, but had selective keeping, in a sense.
Now, all of this occurred that first summer?
That first summer.
And so we were campers.
And A Battery Field Artillery has the highest attendance at our many reunions, our reunions.
We have the greatest esprit because we were persecuted together.
We were persecuted.
We were campers together.
And we had nothing to do but hang with each other.
So when you ask me, what did we do?
Well, we didn't do very much because we couldn't.
I forgot that.
Did y'all have a nickname, your outfit?
No.
Really?
No.
All right.
So what was special about y'all was this pulling together.
They were very much pulled together, yeah.
And by and large, where were your outfit buddies from?
Were they small town Texas?
Small town and country?
Lockhart.
Well, some were.
But we had a lot from Lamar High School.
Houston?
Houston, River Oaks area.
Mm-hmm.

One thing they did do the second semester, this is one of the strengths of A&M at that time, I was in two of my buddies, same level academically, good but not great, not brilliant brains, but good students, on CPA now in Houston, invited me to have lunch with their family sometimes.
And I said, great.
And so one time I went out to one of these parents with country school teachers outside Lockhart, Texas.
Lived in a frame house, very clean, very nice.
Don't be doing that.
But it was very, what you call, extremely modest home.
Then I went down on a train to Houston with Rocco Benowitz and got off the train and got picked up by a chauffeur driver on the other side.
Driven out to River Oaks.
He laughs at this.
I tell this story.
And it seemed like we
father was the executive vice president for Weingarten, grocery chain.
But the thing is, I was totally shocked, because these were just two buddies.
They wore uniform, neither of them could wear a cashmere coat or be in a Jewish fraternity or anything like that.
They were equals.
Now as a historian I say,
If you want absolute equality, you've got to impose those kind of rules.
If you want egalitarianism, you're going to have to have certain rules and regulations, and you lose individual freedoms and so forth.
But it was nice in that aspect for a period of time, but I wouldn't want to live with it permanently.
During that first summer, did you write many letters, get many phone calls?
No, no.
I was pretty self-sufficient.
I had two older brothers.
My mother did not pay a whole lot of attention to me.
She didn't need to.
And you didn't have a steady girlfriend at that point?
I didn't have a steady girlfriend, which is another story we'll come to later on.
So you go home at the end of summer, and what did you tell your family and your folks that A&M was like?
I didn't.
You didn't?
I assumed they knew.
Okay.
You know, their sons had been here.
My grandfather and his son and his son were the first three generations of A&M, and we
We knew what A&M was like.
I did not, I knew what I was getting into when I came in.
I wanted to.
Most of my classmates didn't, but I did.
Now, were most of your classmates, as far as you can recall, first-generation college students?
Did you call me first-generation?
My mother went, but my father didn't.
All right, and you're only home a brief time between summer and fall semester.
Went home Thanksgiving, I think.
All right, then you come back, and now there's a larger enrollment because of the fall semester?
Oh, yeah, when I came back, I came back, I went in the Marines in January 22, 1945, was discharged.
But wait, wait, let's do this fall semester before you leave.
You come back, and were there many first semester fish that fall?
Not many some, but not many.
So most of them, most of the fish had come in the summer.

Because they wanted to squeeze as much college as they could, because we all knew that unless we had some physical, or were very, very young, even the very young assumed that they were going to go into the... Now, when did you become 18th?
I became AT the first of October of 1944.
All right, that fall semester.
Right.
All right, and you're still an engineering major at this point?
No.
You changed.
I changed.
To history.
Changed to history.
Liberal arts, colon, history.
Who did you go, do you remember who you went to talk to about that?
Nobody.
Nobody.
Who did you turn to those first two semesters for any kind of advice?
Nobody.
So you determined...
They had a course you were supposed to take with a catalog.
You just signed up for those courses.
Right, and in the fall, you had fewer labs, so what did you do with your extra time?
Played more sports.
Played more movies.
And that fall, you must have had some of the routine, Aggie routine of football games,
describe going to an Aggie football game as a fish?
One thing we did do, I had a good friend, I knew him, I had known him, Marshall.

I would have labeled him my best friend, who I knew was a great junior high school football player, turned out to be a great high school football player, turned out to be a great college football player, and a great professional football player, named Hawaii Tittle.
we were going to go over and play LSU, and Y.E.
Tittle had gone from Marshall to Texas, where the number one guy was going to be a guy named Bobby Lane, and Y.E.
Tittle saw he was going to be second fiddle to Bobby Lane, so he left Texas and went to LSU.
Yelberton Abraham Tittle.
And so I wanted to go over and see him, and we got instructions from the
administration that we were not to cut Saturday morning classes.

If we did we would be considered absent without leave and we would be severely disciplined and about 700 of us said to heck with you and we got out and hitchhiked about 55th and Line at the East Gate and got a ride in
Finally came in a car that caught on fire as we drove into Navasota.
So I got out there and that was the worst thing that could happen to you because every car going out of Navasota was filled with Aggies.
So another friend and I had to hire a taxi to take us to Hempstead to get on that other highway from Austin to Houston.
So we hired a taxi and got to Hempstead and went over.
So we hitchhiked over and met this other friend of mine, Rocker Benowitz, and we hitchhiked over.
got picked up by a Jewish couple in a big Buick, the biggest Buick they made at the time.
And I told Brock this, and I said, you know, they found his name was Rabinowitz, and they couldn't do enough for us.
Bought us lunch and everything, went over there.
You went all the way to Baton Rouge?
To Baton Rouge.
And I came back, and I got 20 demerits, which put me on academic conduct probation, and wrote a letter to my parents.
My mother wrote back and said,
My Robert, and she had lost one son, I remember.
Robert had my permission to go.
If you want to send him home, please do.
She had lost one son, and she was just as happy to have me home.
And what was the reaction here?
I didn't hear it.
But I saw a copy of the letter.
But you didn't get any.
She came back very hot at them.
But it didn't get you any extra trouble here?
No, no.
Send him home if you want to send him home.
In fact, about how long did the trip from College Station to Baton Rouge take?
Well, we left about noon on Friday.
We did pretty good.
Saturday morning, I think, we got into Baton Rouge.
I know there was nighttime when we were riding in the back of a truck.
open bedded truck from Houston into Beaumont, and it was cold.
And then we got picked up at Beaumont by the Stewart couple, and I guess it was early morning, and they drove us on in.
It's hard to get those foggy.
But coming back was an interesting experience, too, because I was planning on taking the train back, because I wanted to be sure.
I didn't want to hitchhike.
I spent the night at the athletic dorm at LSU.
I was in big trouble because it was noontime and it was Sunday.
And I had to, the game was a night game.
And so while he took me out to the highway, I started filming.
A guy came by and said, I only have a half a tank of gas.
I'm going to Houston, but I don't have any gas tanks.
If you want to take a chance with me, okay.
So I did, and that was before Interstate came around.
And he was talking to these little film stations where you'd park the film station, grocery store kind of thing, going and sweet-talking these Cajun girls.
And they'd fill up his tank of gas and give him some stamps.
He ended up in Houston with a full tank of gas and a full book of stamps.
I'm not lying.
I mean, as a historian, this is the truth.
But he would sweet-talk these.
do all kinds of things.
And so I got to Houston before the train did.
They took a train from Houston on it.
Did people recognize Aggie uniforms in Louisiana?
Oh, yes.
It was a way of life.
The blue lapels.
You got rides easily.
Really easily.
In all of your hitchhiking, did you ever have any negative experience?
No, never.
I have not yet gotten one.
Never, never, never.
No homosexual advances.
I've heard a few of them where the driver was drunk, going too fast, or maybe he'd been drinking a little too much, but nothing worse than that.
Nothing worse than that, drunk.
Let's see, and how did the Aggies come out in that game?
We lost the game 7-0, though there were only 700 or so that were stopped again.
They made a mistake.
People didn't know, Aggie stand of the game.
And they put us down, the terrible seats down at the ground level.
You understand what happened then?
Freshmen at the lowest level, then sophomores, juniors, and seniors standing up.
So everybody all the way back up there had to stand up too.
Said, ow, balance run!
We stopped the game without yelling.
First time that I've ever seen it, you know.
Just the 700 of us yelled so loud that why couldn't we call some of them?
And if anybody today saw the yell leaders in action then, would it have been quite similar to today?
Yes.
There were four then, not five.
Two seniors, two juniors.
But the yells were similar?
Yells were similar, except we had some that they dropped.
When I was back, they used to have Lizzie when we won the ball game.
Have you heard of it?
Is my hat on straight?
Let me hear a powder puff, sweet cherry frosty.
Son of a gun, Lizzie.
And ladies.
We see you, ladies.
We love you, ladies.
So they had those, and they were similar.
Then also they would yell, because they had limited substitution,
One of my friends, Country Higgins, had come off the field.
15 for Higgins.
Every time a substitute came off the field, he got an individual cheer for himself.
Now, during those wartime years, the A&M team was quite young, wasn't it?
Yes, particularly in 1943, the year before we came.
That was the Kitty Corps.
Kitty Corps, yeah.
They did very well.
Our freshman year, we did not do so well.
But they did reasonably well, but it wasn't like the petticoat year.
Right.
When there was a home game, describe the routine for you fish that fall on a Saturday for game day.
You got up, went to class.
Got up, went to class.
And I'm trying to separate what's really fresh of my last three years from my first year.
We did not march in.
It's to the best of my memory.
Was there a Yale practice the night before?
At that time, it was on the steps of the YMCA building.
And it was not at midnight?
It was not at midnight.
We had a guy, the lady was a Rhodes Scholar.
He left here and went to West Point after...
